  "prompt": "What are some good psychological thriller movies of 2015?",
  "response": "2015 was a great year for psychological thrillers, offering a mix of intense, mind-bending, and chilling films. Here are some standout psychological thrillers from that year:\n\n1. **Gone Girl (2014)**  \n   - While technically released in late 2014, *Gone Girl* continued to dominate conversations in 2015. Directed by David Fincher, it\u2019s a gripping tale of marriage, deception, and manipulation based on Gillian Flynn\u2019s novel.\n\n2. **The Gift**  \n   - Directed by Joel Edgerton, this film explores themes of guilt, revenge, and secrets from the past. It\u2019s a tense and unsettling story about a couple whose lives are disrupted by an old acquaintance.\n\n3. **Ex Machina**  \n   - Directed by Alex Garland, this sci-fi psychological thriller delves into artificial intelligence, ethics, and human behavior. It\u2019s a chilling exploration of power dynamics and identity.\n\n4. **The Stanford Prison Experiment**  \n   - Based on the infamous 1971 study, this film delves into the psychological effects of power and control in a simulated prison environment. It\u2019s a claustrophobic and disturbing watch.\n\n5. **Sicario**  \n   - Directed by Denis Villeneuve, this crime thriller has strong psychological elements, focusing on the moral ambiguity and psychological toll of the war on drugs.\n\n6. **The Boy Next Door**  \n   - A psychological thriller starring Jennifer Lopez, it\u2019s about a woman whose life spirals out of control after a brief affair with her neighbor. It\u2019s a tense and suspenseful film.\n\n7. **The Loft**  \n   - Directed by Erik Van Looy, this film revolves around five friends who share a loft for affairs, only to find a dead body there one day. It\u2019s a twisty, suspenseful story.\n\n8. **The Visit**  \n   - Directed by M. Night Shyamalan, this found-footage horror-thriller follows two siblings visiting their estranged grandparents, only to uncover disturbing truths. It\u2019s a mix of psychological tension and horror.\n\n9. **Manglehorn**  \n   - Starring Al Pacino, this film is a slow-burn character study of a lonely man grappling with his past and present. It\u2019s more introspective but has psychological depth.\n\n10. **Regression**  \n    - Directed by Alejandro Amen\u00e1bar, this film stars Ethan Hawke and explores repressed memories and psychological manipulation in a 1950s small town.\n\nThese films offer a range of psychological tension, mind games, and dark storytelling, making 2015 a strong year for the genre.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
